71
00:03:34,290 --> 00:03:34,690
Congratulations.

72
00:03:35,570 --> 00:03:36,570
On the other hand,

73
00:03:37,150 --> 00:03:38,870
there's more to living the good life

74
00:03:38,870 --> 00:03:41,790
that God prescribes,

75
00:03:41,850 --> 00:03:43,090
more to living in what we call

76
00:03:43,090 --> 00:03:44,310
the upside-down kingdom

77
00:03:44,310 --> 00:03:46,660
than just keeping a low profile.

78
00:03:48,510 --> 00:03:49,650
Some of us might be tempted

79
00:03:49,650 --> 00:03:51,490
to feed our egos and starve our souls

80
00:03:51,490 --> 00:03:53,510
by getting lots of attention here.

81
00:03:54,760 --> 00:03:55,980
You know, there's a fine line between,

82
00:03:56,220 --> 00:03:57,180
hey, good sermon, pastor,

83
00:03:57,320 --> 00:03:57,940
and thinking,

84
00:03:58,100 --> 00:04:00,460
hmm, that was a good sermon, wasn't it?

85
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:06,210
But, but there are more ways than one

86
00:04:06,210 --> 00:04:07,290
to mess up our lives.

87
00:04:08,180 --> 00:04:11,240
There are more ways than one to neglect our God

88
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:13,740
and to forget about our relationship with him.

89
00:04:15,350 --> 00:04:17,290
And a lot of these other ways are paths

90
00:04:17,290 --> 00:04:20,290
that aren't just common to people like me

91
00:04:20,290 --> 00:04:22,130
or to David or Kirk.

92
00:04:22,770 --> 00:04:24,630
They are common to everybody.

93
00:04:25,730 --> 00:04:28,210
So let's be brave this morning, and let's be honest.

94
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:32,620
And we're going to find ourselves in Jesus' words

95
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:33,840
if we're both of those things.

96
00:04:34,910 --> 00:04:36,930
Don't hoard treasure down here

97
00:04:36,930 --> 00:04:40,330
where it gets eaten by moths and corroded by rust,

98
00:04:40,450 --> 00:04:42,230
or worse, stolen by burglars.

99
00:04:43,150 --> 00:04:44,350
Stockpile treasure in heaven

100
00:04:44,350 --> 00:04:46,770
where it's safe from moth and rust and burglars.

101
00:04:47,860 --> 00:04:49,000
It's obvious, isn't it?

102
00:04:49,660 --> 00:04:51,340
The place where your treasure is

103
00:04:51,340 --> 00:04:53,400
is the place where you will most want to be

104
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:55,440
and end up being.

105
00:04:56,660 --> 00:05:00,260
Your eyes are windows into your body and soul.

106
00:05:01,550 --> 00:05:04,050
If you open your eyes wide with wonder and belief,

107
00:05:04,710 --> 00:05:06,130
your body fills up with light.

108
00:05:07,170 --> 00:05:09,110
If you live squinty-eyed in greed

109
00:05:09,110 --> 00:05:14,430
and distrust. Your body is a dank cellar. If you pull the blinds on your windows, what

110
00:05:14,430 --> 00:05:21,010
a dark life you will have. You can't worship two gods at once. Loving one god, you'll end

111
00:05:21,010 --> 00:05:26,180
up hating the other. Adoration of one feeds contempt for the other. You can't worship

112
00:05:26,180 --> 00:05:36,400
God and money both. If you decide for God, living a life of God worship, it follows that

113
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:40,940
you don't fuss about what's on the table at mealtimes or whether your clothes in your

114
00:05:40,940 --> 00:05:46,540
closet are ratty or in fashion. There's far more to your life than the food you put in

115
00:05:46,540 --> 00:05:51,540
your stomach. More to your outer appearance than the clothes you hang on your body. Look

116
00:05:51,540 --> 00:05:57,120
at the birds, free and unfettered. Not tied down to a job description, careless in care

117
00:05:57,120 --> 00:06:07,330
of God. And you count far more to him than birds. Excuse me. Has anyone by fussing in

118
00:06:07,330 --> 00:06:12,960
front of a mirror ever gotten taller by so much as an inch? All this time and money

119
00:06:12,960 --> 00:06:17,780
wasted on fashion. Do you think it makes that much of a difference? Instead of looking at

120
00:06:17,780 --> 00:06:24,040
fashions, walk out into the fields and look at the wildflowers. They never primp or shop,

121
00:06:24,750 --> 00:06:30,860
but have you ever seen color and design quite like it? The ten best-dressed men and women

122
00:06:30,860 --> 00:06:37,800
in the country look shabby alongside them. If God gives such attention to the appearance

123
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:43,680
of wildflowers, most of which are never even seen, don't you think he'll attend to you,

124
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:45,060
take pride in you,

125
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:46,360
do his best for you.

126
00:06:48,430 --> 00:06:49,790
What I'm trying to do here

127
00:06:49,790 --> 00:06:50,870
is get you to relax,

128
00:06:51,950 --> 00:06:53,810
to not be so preoccupied with getting

129
00:06:53,810 --> 00:06:55,670
so you can respond to God's giving.

130
00:06:56,590 --> 00:06:58,130
People who don't know God

131
00:06:58,130 --> 00:06:59,310
and the way he works

132
00:06:59,310 --> 00:07:00,550
fuss over these things.

133
00:07:01,270 --> 00:07:02,810
But you know both God

134
00:07:02,810 --> 00:07:04,490
and how he works.

135
00:07:05,510 --> 00:07:07,650
Steep your life in God reality,

136
00:07:08,760 --> 00:07:10,100
in God initiative,

137
00:07:10,940 --> 00:07:11,640
God provisions.

138
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:13,680
Don't worry about missing out.

139
00:07:13,980 --> 00:07:15,220
You'll find all your everyday

140
00:07:15,220 --> 00:07:16,760
human concerns will be met.

141
00:07:18,530 --> 00:07:20,150
Give your entire attention to what

142
00:07:20,150 --> 00:07:21,930
God is doing right now.

143
00:07:22,690 --> 00:07:24,230
And don't get worked up about

144
00:07:24,230 --> 00:07:26,110
what may or may not happen

145
00:07:26,110 --> 00:07:27,610
tomorrow.

146
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:31,400
God will help you deal with whatever

147
00:07:31,400 --> 00:07:33,540
hard things come up when the

148
00:07:33,540 --> 00:07:35,830
time comes. Or as another

149
00:07:35,830 --> 00:07:37,770
translation puts it, tomorrow has

150
00:07:37,770 --> 00:07:38,810
enough worries of its own.

151
00:07:43,490 --> 00:07:45,690
It's a lot to take in, I know. We're taking

152
00:07:45,690 --> 00:07:48,010
this upside-down kingdom passage,

153
00:07:48,150 --> 00:07:50,050
this Sermon on the Mountain, big, huge

154
00:07:50,050 --> 00:07:51,670
leaping jumps

155
00:07:51,670 --> 00:07:53,090
big steps.

156
00:07:54,010 --> 00:07:55,930
But to get you guys

157
00:07:55,930 --> 00:07:57,230
to really let this sink in,

158
00:07:57,750 --> 00:07:59,830
I'm going to ask you to stop for a few minutes.

159
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:03,020
I really, I mean it.

160
00:08:03,060 --> 00:08:05,100
Stop for a few minutes and try

161
00:08:05,100 --> 00:08:07,000
taking the prescription that Jesus is writing

162
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,890
here. Try shutting off all the white

163
00:08:09,890 --> 00:08:10,750
noise for a second.

164
00:08:11,770 --> 00:08:14,370
The distractions and the anxieties in your life.

165
00:08:16,460 --> 00:08:17,780
You know, I'm not even going to give you guys

166
00:08:17,780 --> 00:08:20,080
suggestions about what those distractions

167
00:08:20,080 --> 00:08:21,840
or those anxieties might be

168
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:23,820
because you'll just end up obsessing

169
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:31,130
about what I suggest just to help you out here's a slightly different version

170
00:08:31,130 --> 00:08:37,200
of the last few thoughts in the same teaching about priorities anxiety God

171
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:45,000
perspective so dwell on it therefore do not worry about tomorrow tomorrow will

172
00:08:45,000 --> 00:09:03,940
worry about itself each day has enough trouble of its own okay how many of you

173
00:09:03,940 --> 00:09:10,120
found yourselves thinking something like this ooh all right I'm not going to worry

174
00:09:10,120 --> 00:09:19,570
about X. This is me not worrying about X. See how unconcerned I am about X. It's like

175
00:09:19,570 --> 00:09:26,040
X never happened. Yesterday, at 3.05 p.m., near the Coke machine, with that guy in the

176
00:09:26,040 --> 00:09:33,820
green sweater. It's hard, isn't it? Most of us worry about how we'll manage not worrying

177
00:09:33,820 --> 00:09:37,860
about the things that aren't supposed to worry us tomorrow. I'll try that in a simpler

178
00:09:37,860 --> 00:09:44,550
version. We worry about our inability not to worry when we're really put to it. And

179
00:09:44,550 --> 00:09:49,510
if that proves anything, it proves just this. There's no simple act of self-help or willpower

180
00:09:49,510 --> 00:09:54,570
that's going to allow you to twist your arm into living the kind of life that Jesus prescribes

181
00:09:54,570 --> 00:10:04,180
here. You can't get yourself to say uncle and not worry. Remember, we're talking about

182
00:10:04,180 --> 00:10:11,800
what a kingdom person looks like. And this is not a real estate gain strategy. It's not

183
00:10:11,800 --> 00:10:18,020
a self-help movement. It's a genuine heart changed by God. It's a person who lives in

184
00:10:18,020 --> 00:10:23,420
the rhythms and the natural patterns that come as second nature to people who live in reality

185
00:10:23,420 --> 00:10:30,600
according to God. And unfortunately, most of myself, most of us, including myself, don't live

186
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:36,640
there very often. It's something we need to be taught. Put in a better way, it's a way of thinking

187
00:10:36,640 --> 00:10:43,140
and being that needs to seep down deep inside of us until we can't remember being any other way.

188
00:10:45,510 --> 00:10:48,210
So if you already live a worry-free, God-soaked existence,

189
00:10:48,630 --> 00:10:52,360
then bear with us while the rest of us get our late start.

190
00:10:54,210 --> 00:10:55,790
Here's where Jesus tells us to start.

191
00:10:56,050 --> 00:10:58,670
Don't hoard treasure down here where it gets eaten by moths

192
00:10:58,670 --> 00:11:03,270
and corroded by rust or worse, stolen by burglars.

193
00:11:04,210 --> 00:11:08,530
Stockpile treasure in heaven where it's safe from moth and rust and burglars.

194
00:11:09,110 --> 00:11:10,130
It's obvious, isn't it?

195
00:11:10,410 --> 00:11:11,970
The place where your treasure is

196
00:11:11,970 --> 00:11:15,570
is the place where you will most want to be and end up being,

197
00:11:15,570 --> 00:11:18,930
where your treasure is, your heart will be also.

198
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:21,460
So what does that mean?

199
00:11:21,580 --> 00:11:24,140
Well, here's a common but stupid misconception

200
00:11:24,140 --> 00:11:27,720
about what heaven looks like or what this verse might mean.

201
00:11:28,900 --> 00:11:31,480
Heaven is a kind of bank account that we put money into

202
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:32,800
every time we do something nice,

203
00:11:33,240 --> 00:11:35,540
and we withdraw money from and squander it

204
00:11:35,540 --> 00:11:36,780
every time we do something nasty.

205
00:11:37,260 --> 00:11:40,050
I hope not. I really hope not.

206
00:11:41,240 --> 00:11:43,080
Think of how deeply in hock you are

207
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:45,800
if heaven is a moral checkbook register.

208
00:11:48,710 --> 00:11:52,200
This philosophy works for Santa Claus, fine,

209
00:11:52,740 --> 00:11:54,320
but God doesn't work this way.

210
00:11:55,260 --> 00:12:00,080
What Jesus is talking about here is common sense from God's point of view.

211
00:12:02,250 --> 00:12:04,090
He's saying, all right, folks, what lasts?

212
00:12:04,310 --> 00:12:06,530
The sum of your checking account? Nope.

213
00:12:07,480 --> 00:12:10,660
That circa 1970s furniture you bought when you thought it was trendy?

214
00:12:11,950 --> 00:12:13,820
No. No?

215
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:16,960
Well, I'm telling you outright in case you didn't know.

216
00:12:17,420 --> 00:12:19,460
God lasts. I last.

217
00:12:19,460 --> 00:12:23,960
I don't get stolen or eaten or lost or spent.

218
00:12:25,930 --> 00:12:28,530
And if you have equity in your relationship with me,

219
00:12:29,880 --> 00:12:34,540
then you've opened a line of credit that you can draw from now and into forever.

220
00:12:37,550 --> 00:12:40,010
Stockpiling treasure in heaven doesn't just talk about

221
00:12:40,010 --> 00:12:43,890
some pie-in-the-sky blessedness that we get to feel when we die.

222
00:12:45,770 --> 00:12:48,630
You invest in God, you get God's presence and perspective

223
00:12:48,630 --> 00:12:50,650
in your life in the here and now.

224
00:12:52,220 --> 00:12:54,040
Thinker Dallas Willard puts it like this.

225
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:58,420
Invest your life in what God is doing, which cannot be lost.

226
00:12:58,800 --> 00:13:02,780
Of course, this means that we will invest in our relationship to Jesus himself

227
00:13:02,780 --> 00:13:04,720
and through him to God.

228
00:13:04,800 --> 00:13:07,720
But beyond that, and in close union with it,

229
00:13:08,060 --> 00:13:10,160
we'll devote ourselves to the good of other people,

230
00:13:10,160 --> 00:13:12,920
those around us within the range of our power to affect.

231
00:13:13,960 --> 00:13:16,080
These people are among God's treasures.

232
00:13:17,100 --> 00:13:20,080
The Lord's portion, we're told, is his people.

233
00:13:21,030 --> 00:13:25,150
And that certainly includes ourselves in a unique and fundamental way.

234
00:13:25,270 --> 00:13:29,370
We have the care of our own souls and lives in a way no one else does,

235
00:13:29,930 --> 00:13:33,010
and in a way, we have the care of no one else.

236
00:13:36,670 --> 00:13:40,910
In other words, storing up treasures in heaven is making God himself

237
00:13:40,910 --> 00:13:47,940
and the sort of things that are important to God, like other people, important to you.

238
00:13:48,420 --> 00:13:51,160
And that sounds easy enough, at least until you try it.

239
00:13:52,430 --> 00:13:53,170
Think about it.

240
00:13:53,170 --> 00:13:56,110
Those of you who are married or involved with someone else,

241
00:13:57,170 --> 00:14:00,590
are you thoroughly satisfied with the quantity and quality of time

242
00:14:00,590 --> 00:14:02,150
you've spent with your significant other?

243
00:14:04,560 --> 00:14:07,000
Those of you who are parents or grandparents,

244
00:14:07,220 --> 00:14:10,720
do you have no regrets about the kind of time that you spend

245
00:14:10,720 --> 00:14:15,860
or didn't spend with your kids, your grandkids?

246
00:14:17,060 --> 00:14:19,240
Pick any human relationship. Pick one.

247
00:14:20,050 --> 00:14:24,840
Brother, sister, parent, friend, grocery counter, checkout person.

248
00:14:24,840 --> 00:14:29,410
and ask yourself if you've poured the kind of attention

249
00:14:29,410 --> 00:14:31,710
and love into these relationships

250
00:14:31,710 --> 00:14:32,970
that you wished you could have.

251
00:14:35,290 --> 00:14:37,190
Brass tacks, this is beneath it all.

252
00:14:38,750 --> 00:14:41,940
Are you as close to God as you wish you could be?

253
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:48,660
If you say yes to that last question,

254
00:14:48,940 --> 00:14:52,540
then please finish this spiel for me.

255
00:14:54,430 --> 00:14:55,310
No takers, okay.

256
00:14:56,840 --> 00:14:58,900
See, there's a sad truth about human existence

257
00:14:58,900 --> 00:15:00,840
that Jesus captures in these words.

258
00:15:02,580 --> 00:15:05,380
Your eyes are the windows into your body and soul.

259
00:15:07,130 --> 00:15:09,710
If you open your eyes wide with wonder and belief,

260
00:15:10,090 --> 00:15:11,510
your body fills up with light.

261
00:15:12,690 --> 00:15:15,230
If you live squinty-eyed and greed and distrust,

262
00:15:15,330 --> 00:15:16,630
your body is a dank cellar.

263
00:15:17,310 --> 00:15:19,050
If you pull the blinds on your windows,

264
00:15:19,050 --> 00:15:20,990
what a dark life you'll have.

265
00:15:22,380 --> 00:15:24,020
You can't worship two gods at once.

266
00:15:24,700 --> 00:15:26,620
Loving one god, you'll end up hating the other.

267
00:15:27,460 --> 00:15:31,100
Adoration of one feeds contempt for the other.

268
00:15:31,960 --> 00:15:33,860
You can't worship God and money both.

269
00:15:36,230 --> 00:15:37,350
Here's the sad truth.

270
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:39,380
You drink God in.

271
00:15:40,060 --> 00:15:42,500
You live in a way that just bursts with his greatness,

272
00:15:43,020 --> 00:15:44,600
his love, his generosity.

273
00:15:45,900 --> 00:15:47,240
And your life doesn't end,

274
00:15:47,660 --> 00:15:48,820
even when your pulse stops.

275
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:49,800
Your life doesn't end.

276
00:15:51,180 --> 00:15:52,780
You feed your own appetites,

277
00:15:54,050 --> 00:15:57,130
concern yourself exclusively with looking out for numero uno,

278
00:15:57,630 --> 00:16:02,420
and your life caves in on itself.

279
00:16:03,370 --> 00:16:06,030
It collapses under the weight of its own selfishness.

280
00:16:10,070 --> 00:16:11,990
And too many of us choose this second alternative.

281
00:16:13,710 --> 00:16:14,810
If you don't believe me,

282
00:16:15,430 --> 00:16:18,230
Ask one of the Enron executives who just got a congressional subpoena.

283
00:16:20,940 --> 00:16:24,560
There's a ripe example of what shameless self-interest and greed finally get you.

284
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,940
But, again, since most of us aren't villains on that scale,

285
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:33,620
we should ask ourselves more reasonable questions.

286
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:38,430
How often have you and I failed to cling to the people and things that really matter?

287
00:16:40,570 --> 00:16:45,030
How often have we let ourselves get neck deep in worrying about things that we simply can't change?

288
00:16:47,480 --> 00:16:51,820
I'm not, and Christ is definitely not trying to make anyone feel guilty this morning.

289
00:16:51,820 --> 00:16:54,800
about making the necessary sacrifices

290
00:16:54,800 --> 00:16:59,210
of time and attention that we make to feed our families,

291
00:16:59,450 --> 00:17:01,210
to clothe our families, to feed ourselves.

292
00:17:02,590 --> 00:17:04,930
The Bible has a lot of pointed and nasty things

293
00:17:04,930 --> 00:17:06,350
to say about people who freeload

294
00:17:06,350 --> 00:17:08,730
or people who neglect care for their families.

295
00:17:08,870 --> 00:17:10,230
So storing up treasures in heaven

296
00:17:10,230 --> 00:17:12,990
is not a kind of loophole

297
00:17:12,990 --> 00:17:14,930
for lazy or financially careless people.

298
00:17:15,710 --> 00:17:16,410
Not the point.

299
00:17:17,800 --> 00:17:19,860
But I don't need to harp on this too much, do I?

300
00:17:20,780 --> 00:17:22,000
Especially not in this service.

301
00:17:23,160 --> 00:17:26,860
We all know when we're doing what it takes simply to get by.

302
00:17:27,340 --> 00:17:31,400
Working a job, bringing home the bacon, paying our dues.

303
00:17:32,910 --> 00:17:37,450
What we usually fail to recognize is when we've crossed that very blurry line

304
00:17:37,450 --> 00:17:41,770
between doing what it takes and doing more than it takes

305
00:17:41,770 --> 00:17:46,560
because we want to feed our egos, our pocketbooks, our closets,

306
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:50,380
and when all is said and done, our self-interest.

307
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:56,580
Or, should I say, we usually fail at first to see these sort of things in ourselves.

308
00:17:57,740 --> 00:18:00,580
Seeing it in someone else, though, is easy, right?

309
00:18:01,120 --> 00:18:02,580
It's always easier to point the finger.

310
00:18:07,200 --> 00:18:12,140
See, Jesus doesn't give us a hard and fast definition of what a selfish person looks like.

311
00:18:13,140 --> 00:18:17,420
There's no exhaustive definition, no way you can encompass that exactly.

312
00:18:17,820 --> 00:18:22,260
He just makes fun of the characteristically self-absorbed things that we do

313
00:18:22,260 --> 00:18:25,980
by explaining how far out of whack we are when we behave that way.

314
00:18:27,230 --> 00:18:33,850
He makes fun of us, and we see ourselves, if we're honest, in his description, in his derision.

315
00:18:34,710 --> 00:18:40,070
Has anyone, by fussing in front of a mirror, ever gotten taller so much as by an inch?

316
00:18:40,690 --> 00:18:44,890
All this time and money wasted on fashion, do you think it makes that much difference?

317
00:18:45,750 --> 00:18:49,250
Instead of looking at fashions, walk out into the fields and look at the wildflowers.

318
00:18:49,610 --> 00:18:55,550
They never primp or shop, but have you ever seen color and design quite like it?

319
00:18:56,600 --> 00:18:58,840
The ten best-dressed men and women in the country

320
00:18:58,840 --> 00:19:00,380
look shabby alongside them.

321
00:19:01,660 --> 00:19:03,000
I love that rendering right there.

322
00:19:04,320 --> 00:19:07,480
If God gives such attention to the appearance of wildflowers,

323
00:19:07,980 --> 00:19:09,800
most of which are never even seen,

324
00:19:11,510 --> 00:19:13,090
are here today and gone tomorrow,

325
00:19:14,350 --> 00:19:15,890
don't you think he'll attend to you?

326
00:19:16,870 --> 00:19:18,890
Take pride in you, do his best for you.

327
00:19:19,090 --> 00:19:21,350
What I'm trying to do here is get you to relax,

328
00:19:21,350 --> 00:19:23,190
to not be so preoccupied with getting,

329
00:19:23,610 --> 00:19:25,390
so you can respond to God's giving.

330
00:19:26,640 --> 00:19:28,800
People who don't know God and the way he works

331
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:34,930
fuss over these things, but you know both God and how he works. Steep your life in God

332
00:19:34,930 --> 00:19:41,570
reality, God initiative, God provisions. Don't worry about missing out. You'll find all your

333
00:19:41,570 --> 00:19:50,460
everyday human concerns will be met. This sermon preaches itself. I don't need to embellish

334
00:19:50,460 --> 00:19:57,580
it much. Jesus makes the point. What do you need to hear from me, really? I'll add this.

335
00:19:57,800 --> 00:20:02,440
There's a lot more sober way of looking at the dilemma that we face between steeping

336
00:20:02,440 --> 00:20:08,650
our lives in God-reality, God-initiative, God-provisions, or just looking out for number

337
00:20:08,650 --> 00:20:15,360
one and obsessing about number one the whole time we're doing it. And Stephen King writes

338
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:20,410
it in his screenplay for the Shawshank Redemption, which many of you may have seen. He puts it

339
00:20:20,410 --> 00:20:29,570
in the mouth of his character. You get busy living, or you get busy dying. My upside-down

340
00:20:29,570 --> 00:20:33,930
kingdom paraphrase, you get busy living a life that stretches into forever, you get

341
00:20:33,930 --> 00:20:40,560
busy living the kingdom life, or you get busy worrying about whether or not you want a coffin

342
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:49,190
in mahogany or cedar with mother-of-pearl inlay. It's harsh, but it's the truth when all is said

343
00:20:49,190 --> 00:20:58,000
and done. In the five years that my wife and I have been married, we have buried a family member

344
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:04,580
every single one of those years. Three of them were grandparents on both sides of the family.

345
00:21:04,580 --> 00:21:11,200
One was an uncle who died very young of AIDS that he contracted through a blood transfusion

346
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:13,100
before they knew to screen for that sort of thing.

347
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:17,170
So it was a very hard and kind of senseless death.

348
00:21:18,760 --> 00:21:23,870
And so we've been to one funeral for every anniversary we've had.

349
00:21:25,240 --> 00:21:30,100
And I've been to funerals here, too, for many of the saints that have left this place.

350
00:21:33,890 --> 00:21:38,440
And there's two kinds of funerals, as far as I can tell.

351
00:21:40,300 --> 00:21:45,760
They're the funerals that are celebrations of a life well lived.

352
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:56,290
And there are funerals where you're just struggling to come up with something substantial, kind to say about the person who's left.

353
00:21:57,030 --> 00:21:58,830
How many of you knew Mike Savolka?

354
00:22:06,050 --> 00:22:09,440
Mike was a fantastic man.

355
00:22:09,440 --> 00:22:15,660
He could see if he held the paper about yea far from his face,

356
00:22:15,880 --> 00:22:21,160
but he was still doing it in the choir every Wednesday night.

357
00:22:21,960 --> 00:22:27,920
I'm told that in his last days when he was dying in the hospital,

358
00:22:28,460 --> 00:22:33,140
he was keeping his roommates awake by singing really loudly and brashly.

359
00:22:33,480 --> 00:22:34,340
Praises to God.

360
00:22:34,480 --> 00:22:37,620
I mean, the man did not go down with a whimper.

361
00:22:37,620 --> 00:22:41,240
and who was at his funeral.

362
00:22:43,440 --> 00:22:46,340
Person after person after person

363
00:22:46,340 --> 00:22:49,880
just gushing about this guy

364
00:22:49,880 --> 00:22:51,460
in a way that you just can't manufacture.

365
00:22:52,020 --> 00:22:53,280
I mean, there was one point

366
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:54,880
where one of his young grandsons

367
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:56,540
was talking about Mike Savolka

368
00:22:56,540 --> 00:22:59,000
and all the great things that Mike Savolka was to him.

369
00:22:59,340 --> 00:23:01,480
The kingdom life that Mike Savolka led.

370
00:23:01,920 --> 00:23:03,680
And the officiator of the ceremony

371
00:23:03,680 --> 00:23:04,480
had to sort of say,

372
00:23:04,560 --> 00:23:06,880
oh, okay, we're on the clock here.

373
00:23:07,260 --> 00:23:07,840
Time's up.

374
00:23:08,580 --> 00:23:10,840
I mean, they had to stop people

375
00:23:10,840 --> 00:23:16,340
from giving just a glowing report on the sort of man Mike Savolka was.

376
00:23:16,340 --> 00:23:24,470
I had Jenny's grandfather, her dad's father, had the same sort of funeral.

377
00:23:24,570 --> 00:23:27,990
We told jokes at his funeral because that's what would honor him the most.

378
00:23:28,070 --> 00:23:31,850
If he wanted to be remembered for something, he wanted to be remembered for his humor.

379
00:23:33,710 --> 00:23:34,770
It was a celebration.

380
00:23:35,590 --> 00:23:38,510
And yes, we all cried when the casket got lowered into the ground,

381
00:23:39,030 --> 00:23:41,650
and yes, that ripped our guts out.

382
00:23:41,650 --> 00:23:50,990
But you walked away just feeling God was in that life.

383
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:56,770
My father-in-law, Walt White, is a missionary in Bangladesh.

384
00:23:57,850 --> 00:24:01,560
And life in Bangladesh is hard.

385
00:24:01,720 --> 00:24:04,700
It's brutish, nasty, and short.

386
00:24:05,830 --> 00:24:11,790
And they have a saying there that if someone dies quickly in their sleep,

387
00:24:11,910 --> 00:24:13,970
then they must have been a good man, a godly man.

388
00:24:14,410 --> 00:24:16,490
That's the best you can hope for in Bangladesh.

389
00:24:17,130 --> 00:24:19,950
And when Walt went back to his mission field

390
00:24:19,950 --> 00:24:23,310
and told people who had known him most of his adult life

391
00:24:23,310 --> 00:24:24,410
about his father passing,

392
00:24:24,930 --> 00:24:27,020
they said, well, how did he die?

393
00:24:27,880 --> 00:24:29,860
And they didn't care really about the life he'd kind of lived.

394
00:24:29,920 --> 00:24:31,920
They just wanted to know, almost superstitiously,

395
00:24:32,180 --> 00:24:34,100
how did this man pass into the next life?

396
00:24:34,140 --> 00:24:37,770
Was it quick, painless, and over in a few moments?

397
00:24:37,910 --> 00:24:41,050
And when he said yes, they all said, ah, what a godly man.

398
00:24:42,410 --> 00:24:46,490
Now that's not a good litmus test for what makes a kingdom person,

399
00:24:46,490 --> 00:24:47,550
what makes a godly man.

400
00:24:47,770 --> 00:24:50,910
There are good people that die slowly, unfortunately.

401
00:24:53,490 --> 00:24:56,600
There are bad people that die quickly, unfortunately.

402
00:24:59,560 --> 00:25:05,170
But we all know how these people look when they pass on.

403
00:25:07,680 --> 00:25:11,400
So I think a good way to sum up this passage,

404
00:25:12,300 --> 00:25:14,040
don't let tomorrow worry about itself.

405
00:25:14,520 --> 00:25:15,800
Let tomorrow worry about itself.

406
00:25:15,920 --> 00:25:16,960
Seek first God's kingdom,

407
00:25:18,390 --> 00:25:20,790
is paraphrased well in this bumper sticker

408
00:25:20,790 --> 00:25:22,590
that my sister used to have in her truck.

409
00:25:23,330 --> 00:25:25,250
Live so the preacher won't have to lie at your funeral.

410
00:25:33,070 --> 00:25:35,090
My, she did enjoy Las Vegas.

411
00:25:36,220 --> 00:25:39,400
That slot machine was her very favorite thing in the world to do.

412
00:25:39,480 --> 00:25:41,420
You know, something lame like that.

413
00:25:45,700 --> 00:25:47,460
Because that's what it all boils down to.

414
00:25:48,540 --> 00:25:50,880
We're supposed to be living from God's perspective, folks.

415
00:25:50,920 --> 00:25:55,040
We're supposed to be living habitually in God's power.

416
00:25:55,790 --> 00:25:57,750
Doing the sort of things that God is doing.

417
00:25:59,110 --> 00:26:02,170
Speaking in a way that God would have you speak to your fellow person.

418
00:26:03,740 --> 00:26:06,800
And I said, that's not a self-help manual.

419
00:26:06,800 --> 00:26:14,820
That's a habit that you get into the process of living only because the strength of God is poured day in and day out into your life.

420
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:23,200
God, Christ, is inviting you into that kind of God-soaked life through this passage.

421
00:26:24,560 --> 00:26:26,620
He's inviting you into the upside-down kingdom.

422
00:26:27,740 --> 00:26:31,840
Because the 401K, the upside-down 401K, is a relationship with him.

423
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:35,480
It's a relationship that spills into every area of your life.

424
00:26:36,820 --> 00:26:38,220
And that's what he wants from you.

425
00:26:39,560 --> 00:26:41,160
I'm going to call the worship team up.

426
00:26:41,600 --> 00:26:50,700
Behind me? David? David? Okay. David is currently in the choir room. Please join us. Thank you.

427
00:26:53,550 --> 00:27:05,060
And I'm going to ask them to play quietly. And while they play, I don't want you to think too

428
00:27:05,060 --> 00:27:13,370
hard about this. I just want you to say, God, I'm looking in my soul, and I'm seeing that

429
00:27:13,370 --> 00:27:23,140
what you talk about and what I am are different. They're not meeting up. I want a little more

430
00:27:23,140 --> 00:27:29,040
one-to-one correspondence between your description of the upside-down kingdom and my life. I

431
00:27:29,040 --> 00:27:38,000
want your power to be that, to do that. If you want prayer, if you want us to just ask

432
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:44,090
God on your behalf, God, smother this person with your presence, we'll do that. I'll do

433
00:27:44,090 --> 00:27:50,170
that. Kirk will do that. The deacons and deaconesses will do that. If you want to turn

434
00:27:50,170 --> 00:27:57,590
to the person who you came with this morning and ask them simply, could you pray for me?

435
00:27:58,550 --> 00:28:01,290
Could I have a little bit more one-to-one correspondence

436
00:28:01,290 --> 00:28:08,190
between this kind of great life, this good life, and my life?

437
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:10,960
Then do it. There's no shame here.

438
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:13,300
You don't have to worry about what people will think.

439
00:28:13,540 --> 00:28:16,420
How many people think that anybody completely arrived,

440
00:28:16,560 --> 00:28:19,120
completely measured up to the things that I talked about this morning?

441
00:28:19,180 --> 00:28:21,580
I will be the first to admit that I'm not there.

442
00:28:22,180 --> 00:28:26,080
I get there from moment to moment, but it's just a moment, a fleeting moment.

443
00:28:26,080 --> 00:28:28,830
I pray that in my life

444
00:28:28,830 --> 00:28:30,350
those moments will get longer

445
00:28:30,350 --> 00:28:31,930
and more protracted

446
00:28:31,930 --> 00:28:37,160
I pray that the preacher

447
00:28:37,160 --> 00:28:38,400
won't have to lie at my funeral

448
00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:41,790
let's pray together

449
00:28:41,790 --> 00:28:49,410
God do your thing in us

450
00:28:49,410 --> 00:28:54,320
help us to lay down all the things

451
00:28:54,320 --> 00:28:56,830
that we obsess about

452
00:28:56,830 --> 00:28:58,950
the things that get in the way

453
00:28:58,950 --> 00:29:00,690
of just being with you

454
00:29:00,690 --> 00:29:01,570
loving you

455
00:29:01,570 --> 00:29:04,740
loving the people that you've given us to love

456
00:29:04,740 --> 00:29:07,740
help us to clear

457
00:29:07,740 --> 00:29:11,080
the path for your work

458
00:29:11,080 --> 00:29:13,020
in our life. Help us to do a little

459
00:29:13,020 --> 00:29:14,420
spring cleaning in our souls.

460
00:29:16,990 --> 00:29:18,810
Most of all, God, once we've swept the place

461
00:29:18,810 --> 00:29:20,970
clean, fill us with your presence so the change

462
00:29:20,970 --> 00:29:22,550
becomes lasting

463
00:29:22,550 --> 00:29:25,190
and noticeable.

464
00:29:27,620 --> 00:29:29,720
We pray these things because you're the only one who can

465
00:29:29,720 --> 00:29:31,900
do it. You're the only one capable

466
00:29:31,900 --> 00:29:33,780
of fulfilling these promises because you're

467
00:29:33,780 --> 00:29:36,030
the one who made them and you have

468
00:29:36,030 --> 00:29:40,440
the credentials. In Jesus' name

469
00:29:40,440 --> 00:29:41,340
I pray these things.

